  "response": "Quora actually changed their font twice on December 20th, 2016. Here's a breakdown of why they did it:\n\n*   **Initial Change:** Quora initially changed the font to **Industry**. This font was intended to improve readability and modernize the site's look.\n*   **Rollback and Second Change:** However, this change was met with **significant user backlash.** Many users complained that the new font was difficult to read, especially for longer answers. In response to the negative feedback, Quora **rolled back the change**.\n    *   Then, later the same day, they made a **second font change**, this time to **FF Meta.** This font was also intended to improve readability, but it was chosen based on being seen as a better option than Industry.\n*   **Why the Need for a Font Change?:** Quora, like any website, constantly looks for ways to improve the user experience. Font changes are often part of that process, with the goals of:\n    *   **Improved Readability:** Making text easier to read reduces eye strain and improves engagement.\n    *   **Modern Look and Feel:** Updating the font can help a website feel more current and visually appealing.\n    *   **Brand Consistency:** Ensuring the font aligns with the overall brand identity.\n\nIn short, Quora changed the font on December 20th, 2016, because they believed it would improve the user experience. The initial change didn't go over well, so they quickly reverted it and then implemented a different font.",
